      <br/>
        <p><strong>WORKING TOWARD A LEVEL PLAYING FIELD </strong></p>
        <br/>
        <p class="">The reality of a level playing field for girls in Tanzania and other East African countries was aspirational at best. But Ashley took on the community’s ask, raising funds for building and opening the first secondary school in Lashaine Village in 2008.</p>
        <br/>
        <p class="">But she knew one school wasn’t going to be enough.</p>
        <br/>
        <p class="">There’s an entire generation of girls and boys being left behind in Tanzania. Providing education and support to girls, especially those between the ages of 11 and 17, improves individual lives and families, and it has more impact in changing the next generation for the better than any other cause.</p>
        <br/>
        <p class="">That’s why Ashley founded the Red Sweater Project in 2011, with the goal of getting as many East African kids as possible in into a school uniform, or “red sweater.” In 2012, Ashley opened the Mungere School, which welcomes a new class of students each year. She’s dedicated herself to developing quality, sustainable and accessible schools for East African children. And she’s just getting started.</p>

